The news represents a major escalation of the food adulteration scandal, which has called into question whether supermarkets have any idea what goes in to their products.

Concerns about illegal horse meat contamination of burgers first emerged two weeks ago when Tesco and Iceland were named as selling tainted burgers in the UK.

Separately, these stores, together with Aldi and Lidl, were doing the same in their supermarkets in Ireland.

Evidence emerged today that it is likely that tens of millions of burgers containing horse meat have been sold to British families since May of last year.

The Co-op’s and Asda’s were manufactured by a company called Silvercrest, which is part of ABP Foods, based in County Monaghan in southern Ireland.

The same company was also responsible for making contaminated burgers for Tesco, where the meat content was up to 29per cent horse.

